What is LinkedHashSet?
1-LinkedHashSet is a collection class in Java that implements the Set interface.
2-It stores unique elements (no duplicates allowed).
3-Unlike HashSet, which does not guarantee any order,
LinkedHashSet maintains insertion order of the elements.
4-It is backed by a hash table and a doubly-linked list internally.
5-It allows one null element.

It provides constant-time performance for basic operations
like add, remove, and contains, assuming good hash function distribution.

Key Properties of LinkedHashSet:
| Feature           | Details                                                             |
| ----------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Maintains Order   | Yes, preserves the order in which elements were inserted            |
| Allows Duplicates | No, duplicates are ignored                                          |
| Allows Null       | Yes, one null element is allowed                                    |
| Thread Safety     | Not synchronized, should be externally synchronized if needed       |
| Performance       | Similar to HashSet, O(1) average time for add, remove, and contains |


When to Use LinkedHashSet?
When you need a collection with no duplicates and order preservation.
For example, storing unique elements and iterating over them in the order they were added.
When you want better iteration order predictability than HashSet.

Summary:
LinkedHashSet preserves insertion order.
Duplicate elements are ignored.
One null element is allowed.
Supports all basic set operations like add, remove, contains, clear.
Iteration order matches the order of insertion.

